Non-traditional Pathways into Game Development

3
00:00:12,625 --> 00:00:15,426
as part of the Game Career Seminar at GDC.

4
00:00:15,426 --> 00:00:18,107
So for today's session, we'll each be talking

5
00:00:18,107 --> 00:00:19,807
about our paths into the games industry

6
00:00:19,807 --> 00:00:23,329
and then we'll have a panel about

7
00:00:23,329 --> 00:00:25,909
what we learned on our journeys,

8
00:00:25,909 --> 00:00:27,470
where things have overlapped for us

9
00:00:27,470 --> 00:00:29,311
and what has helped and what hasn't helped.

10
00:00:29,311 --> 00:00:32,652
So we're very excited you can join us.

11
00:00:32,652 --> 00:00:33,592
And before we dive in,

12
00:00:34,889 --> 00:00:37,670
Here are our panelists for today.

13
00:00:37,670 --> 00:00:39,231
We'll each do our own introductions

14
00:00:39,231 --> 00:00:40,931
as part of our individual talks.

15
00:00:40,931 --> 00:00:44,193
So let's start those now with Erika.

16
00:00:44,193 --> 00:00:44,533
All right.

17
00:00:44,533 --> 00:00:47,714
So thank you for coming.

18
00:00:47,714 --> 00:00:50,355
My name is Erika Mariko Olsen.

19
00:00:50,815 --> 00:00:58,140
and I currently work as a publishing producer at Humble Bundle. Why am I here? This is the slide

20
00:00:58,140 --> 00:01:03,424
just to tell you that I've been associated with different companies or IPs, so I have

21
00:01:03,424 --> 00:01:07,767
been in the industry for a little while, but this wasn't my first career.

22
00:01:09,590 --> 00:01:13,792
So this is what my resume looked like before joining the games

23
00:01:13,792 --> 00:01:17,874
industry. That's not to say that I didn't want to be in the

24
00:01:17,874 --> 00:01:22,616
games industry. I've been a gamer my entire life. But I

25
00:01:22,616 --> 00:01:26,818
didn't really have any role models or mentors growing up who

26
00:01:26,818 --> 00:01:30,540
encouraged me in that direction. So I really just had no idea it

27
00:01:30,540 --> 00:01:31,920
was even on the table.

28
00:01:32,999 --> 00:01:41,164
So my past resume, most recruiters and hiring managers would look at this and really see zero connection to the games industry.

29
00:01:41,164 --> 00:01:44,586
And yet I've now been in the industry for eight years.

30
00:01:44,586 --> 00:01:51,630
So I'm going to super quickly take us backwards through my games career so that we can kind of explore where those intersect.

31
00:01:53,255 --> 00:01:56,578
So currently working as a publishing producer at Humble Games,

32
00:01:56,578 --> 00:01:58,840
and I also did the same thing for Stadia.

33
00:01:58,840 --> 00:02:03,924
This is primarily working with external teams on multiple projects.

34
00:02:03,924 --> 00:02:07,347
And before that, I worked at Riot Games as an in-house producer,

35
00:02:07,347 --> 00:02:11,031
focusing on internal teams and their overall work systems.

36
00:02:11,031 --> 00:02:16,275
And I moved through a couple of different roles at Riot.

37
00:02:16,275 --> 00:02:19,278
And I started my career in the games industry,

38
00:02:19,278 --> 00:02:20,959
full-time at least, in recruiting.

39
00:02:22,834 --> 00:02:27,358
So I'm going to talk a little bit about how did I get here,

40
00:02:27,358 --> 00:02:29,920
because it wasn't 100% intentional.

41
00:02:29,920 --> 00:02:33,123
But I do think it happened because of these four things,

42
00:02:33,123 --> 00:02:36,506
networking and volunteering, timing and luck,

43
00:02:36,506 --> 00:02:39,188
identifying skills without perfect context,

44
00:02:39,188 --> 00:02:40,649
and convincing others.

45
00:02:42,618 --> 00:02:47,260
So networking and volunteering. After graduating college, I was

46
00:02:47,260 --> 00:02:51,823
volunteering at Sakura Con and Anime Expo. It's, you know, not

47
00:02:51,823 --> 00:02:55,384
quite the video games industry, but it is adjacent. There's lots

48
00:02:55,384 --> 00:02:59,327
of anime lovers in the games industry. And

49
00:02:59,896 --> 00:03:19,782
The thing to note about networking is that it's really not just about meeting the right people. It's an opportunity for you to be building your social skills, hopefully making friendships that last, you know, beyond just the one time. You're building credibility in a space that you care about, especially with volunteer work.

50
00:03:20,122 --> 00:03:22,283
and you're making your skills and passions known,

51
00:03:22,283 --> 00:03:24,984
and you're creating an interesting bullet point

52
00:03:24,984 --> 00:03:26,244
on your resume.

53
00:03:26,244 --> 00:03:29,505
A lot of recruiters look at these things on my resume

54
00:03:29,505 --> 00:03:31,145
and they just want to know more about it

55
00:03:31,145 --> 00:03:33,866
because it's kind of unique.

56
00:03:33,866 --> 00:03:36,687
But a key concept here is to be willing to give

57
00:03:36,687 --> 00:03:39,587
before expecting to receive.

58
00:03:39,587 --> 00:03:42,948
And one little bonus I'd like to add about volunteering,

59
00:03:42,948 --> 00:03:46,009
because I do think it is the best form of networking.

60
00:03:46,517 --> 00:03:59,315
If you, for example, you know, maybe you have student loan debt and you can't necessarily afford to attend the types of events that you want to, volunteering is a really great place to get in for free.

61
00:03:59,315 --> 00:04:03,301
Alright, so now timing and luck. So

62
00:04:03,842 --> 00:04:09,303
we don't really get the opportunities, we don't get control over what opportunities are presented

63
00:04:09,303 --> 00:04:15,884
to us, but you have control over saying yes or no, and you can try to maximize the number of

64
00:04:15,884 --> 00:04:22,706
opportunities that come your way through that prerequisite networking. The reality is that a

65
00:04:22,706 --> 00:04:28,787
lot of jobs in the games industry need to be filled really fast, and so you want to be remembered.

66
00:04:29,127 --> 00:04:32,891
so that people will think to reach out to you when the time comes.

67
00:04:32,891 --> 00:04:36,975
A lot of times there isn't really time to have a thorough interview process

68
00:04:36,975 --> 00:04:39,057
and consider a whole lot of candidates.

69
00:04:39,057 --> 00:04:43,581
Again, they're just trying to get somebody to do the job fast.

70
00:04:43,581 --> 00:04:49,587
And so, because I had proven to be reliable and organized during my volunteer work,

71
00:04:49,587 --> 00:04:54,711
I was remembered and asked by another volunteer to help on BlazBlue Chronophantasma.

72
00:04:57,082 --> 00:04:59,641
All right, so here's where it starts to get a little bit harder.

73
00:05:00,646 --> 00:05:07,711
You want to be able to break down the things that you do into their most basic pieces.

74
00:05:07,711 --> 00:05:13,135
And then if there is another role in the industry that you're looking to transition to,

75
00:05:13,135 --> 00:05:19,420
I encourage you to talk to people in those roles and really break down what is it that they do.

76
00:05:19,420 --> 00:05:26,965
And you'll often find that there's a lot of similarities and you'll be able to articulate them.

77
00:05:27,505 --> 00:05:31,267
even though they were not necessarily in the same context.

78
00:05:31,267 --> 00:05:34,828
So just for an example here,

79
00:05:34,828 --> 00:05:38,269
here's some of the typical things that you might do

80
00:05:38,269 --> 00:05:41,690
in these two non-games industry roles,

81
00:05:41,690 --> 00:05:44,531
but how can we rearticulate them

82
00:05:44,531 --> 00:05:47,733
in a way that applies to being a producer?

83
00:05:47,733 --> 00:05:50,393
And so, as you can see, like, you know,

84
00:05:50,393 --> 00:05:53,034
a lot of this stuff is just rewording it

85
00:05:53,034 --> 00:05:55,235
into a way that applies into.

86
00:05:56,202 --> 00:05:58,422
our roles in the industry.

87
00:05:58,422 --> 00:06:01,183
And your previous experience may not

88
00:06:01,183 --> 00:06:04,004
be one-to-one with what you want to do next,

89
00:06:04,004 --> 00:06:09,186
but the combination of your previous experiences

90
00:06:09,186 --> 00:06:13,888
can merge into checking all of the boxes for the next thing.

91
00:06:13,888 --> 00:06:16,509
So again, it's not perfect context, obviously,

92
00:06:16,509 --> 00:06:18,269
because it's not from the games industry,

93
00:06:18,269 --> 00:06:21,110
but they are the same transferable skills.

94
00:06:21,110 --> 00:06:21,270
All right.

95
00:06:24,012 --> 00:06:26,873
So now the actual hard part is convincing others.

96
00:06:26,873 --> 00:06:29,615
There are a lot of people in the industry

97
00:06:29,615 --> 00:06:31,176
who look for that perfect context.

98
00:06:31,176 --> 00:06:34,737
They want you to have games industry experience in order

99
00:06:34,737 --> 00:06:36,158
to work in the games industry.

100
00:06:36,158 --> 00:06:40,160
And it is kind of this Catch-22 situation.

101
00:06:40,160 --> 00:06:42,462
There are people with a very fixed mindset,

102
00:06:42,462 --> 00:06:44,243
and they're not going to be convinced.

103
00:06:44,243 --> 00:06:46,984
But there obviously are people who can be convinced.

104
00:06:46,984 --> 00:06:49,606
We have a whole panel of people who took different routes

105
00:06:49,606 --> 00:06:52,027
into the games industry.

106
00:06:52,027 --> 00:06:52,127
So.

107
00:06:53,057 --> 00:06:55,219
Just remember that you don't have to do it alone.

108
00:06:55,219 --> 00:06:58,601
You will find allies and advocates and mentors

109
00:06:58,601 --> 00:07:01,704
who are going to help you and are going to talk you

110
00:07:01,704 --> 00:07:04,427
through breaking down all of your core competencies

111
00:07:04,427 --> 00:07:07,349
and skills and applying them into the industry.

112
00:07:07,349 --> 00:07:10,292
So we're out there, and we're willing to help you

113
00:07:10,292 --> 00:07:11,813
if you'll let us.

114
00:07:11,813 --> 00:07:15,136
And with that, I'm going to pass it on to Osama.

115
00:07:17,192 --> 00:07:17,993
Thank you, Erica.

116
00:07:17,993 --> 00:07:20,454
Well, hello, my name's Osama Dorias,

117
00:07:20,454 --> 00:07:23,075
and I'm the lead game designer at WB Games in Montreal.

118
00:07:23,075 --> 00:07:25,716
I'm a game design teacher at Dawson College,

119
00:07:25,716 --> 00:07:28,917
and one of the three Habibis on the Habibis podcast.

120
00:07:28,917 --> 00:07:32,238
Here are some of the games that I've contributed to

121
00:07:32,238 --> 00:07:34,079
over the last 14 years in the industry.

122
00:07:36,217 --> 00:07:39,019
I'd like to start my story at the beginning.

123
00:07:39,019 --> 00:07:41,262
In 1979, a young boy was born in Iraq.

124
00:07:41,262 --> 00:07:43,864
Little did he know he was about to embark

125
00:07:43,864 --> 00:07:47,087
on a great adventure that spanned many continents,

126
00:07:47,087 --> 00:07:48,809
experiences, and careers.

127
00:07:49,885 --> 00:07:53,428
As most kids do, I loved making up games as a kid.

128
00:07:53,428 --> 00:07:57,491
And I do so on the playground with my friends and siblings.

129
00:07:57,491 --> 00:07:58,311
But it didn't stop there.

130
00:07:58,311 --> 00:08:03,274
I actually also loved designing card games and board games.

131
00:08:03,274 --> 00:08:05,936
One of my earliest memories is asking my father

132
00:08:05,936 --> 00:08:08,178
to bring home an empty pizza box.

133
00:08:08,178 --> 00:08:10,820
He was baffled, but he complied.

134
00:08:10,820 --> 00:08:14,562
And when I had that box, I created a board game

135
00:08:14,562 --> 00:08:15,483
inside of it.

136
00:08:15,939 --> 00:08:21,042
So the inside of the box was where the game was, and when you closed the box,

137
00:08:21,042 --> 00:08:26,646
that was the container of the game. And I still find that incredibly clever to this day.

138
00:08:26,646 --> 00:08:33,930
As I got older, I moved on to making maps for video games like Duke Nukem, StarCraft,

139
00:08:33,930 --> 00:08:40,474
Heroes of Might and Magic, Unreal Tournament. This is one of the maps I made in the back.

140
00:08:40,474 --> 00:08:44,637
This hobby persisted into my 20s, but I'm getting ahead of myself.

141
00:08:45,643 --> 00:08:52,646
In addition to making games and maps for games as a kid, I also loved legos and building things.

142
00:08:52,646 --> 00:08:58,589
So naturally, I wanted to be an architect. That was my dream. I wanted to design gorgeous,

143
00:08:58,589 --> 00:09:02,950
elaborate spaces. This was my dream from a very young age,

144
00:09:02,950 --> 00:09:07,512
but right before applying to colleges, I kind of had a change of heart.

145
00:09:08,411 --> 00:09:13,995
and suddenly I felt directionless. I didn't know what to do with my life.

146
00:09:13,995 --> 00:09:18,438
That's a really scary feeling, especially for a 17-year-old.

147
00:09:18,438 --> 00:09:22,541
I decided to major in political science because it was a study that interested me,

148
00:09:22,541 --> 00:09:25,583
even though I really didn't have any real desire to work in the field.

149
00:09:25,583 --> 00:09:33,268
And after university, I got a job as a shipping agent. I kind of had a love-hate relationship

150
00:09:33,268 --> 00:09:37,971
with it. I loved going on ships and meeting the captain and the crew from all over the world,

151
00:09:38,881 --> 00:09:44,164
But I hated doing the customs paperwork.

152
00:09:44,164 --> 00:09:47,246
I did learn a lot from my time as a shipping agent, though.

153
00:09:47,246 --> 00:09:51,909
I had to have impeccable work ethic and punctuality.

154
00:09:51,909 --> 00:09:53,550
Paperwork had to be ready on time.

155
00:09:53,550 --> 00:09:55,532
I couldn't be late or the ship would be delayed,

156
00:09:55,532 --> 00:09:58,674
and that could cost millions of dollars to the client.

157
00:09:58,674 --> 00:10:02,636
I learned to be organized and have impeccable attention

158
00:10:02,636 --> 00:10:03,837
to detail.

159
00:10:03,837 --> 00:10:06,119
One wrong number in the wrong field

160
00:10:06,119 --> 00:10:07,700
could cost a small fortune.

161
00:10:08,420 --> 00:10:11,883
I learned to respect process, even when I didn't like it.

162
00:10:11,883 --> 00:10:14,826
I learned to communicate and negotiate.

163
00:10:14,826 --> 00:10:18,569
But most importantly, I developed my emotional intelligence.

164
00:10:18,569 --> 00:10:21,031
When you work with so many people from all over the world

165
00:10:21,031 --> 00:10:23,473
with different customs and backgrounds,

166
00:10:23,473 --> 00:10:26,136
you quickly learn how to identify shared values

167
00:10:26,136 --> 00:10:27,577
and how to speak to those values.

168
00:10:29,590 --> 00:10:34,514
I eventually quit that job and I started freelancing as a graphic and web designer.

169
00:10:34,514 --> 00:10:35,335
I was self-taught.

170
00:10:35,335 --> 00:10:37,456
I dabbled in it in my teens.

171
00:10:37,456 --> 00:10:40,578
I made a website for my dad's business at one point.

172
00:10:40,578 --> 00:10:45,302
And I'm a pretty fast learner, so it didn't take me long to line up some clients and get

173
00:10:45,302 --> 00:10:45,802
some work.

174
00:10:45,802 --> 00:10:48,664
I eventually learned Flash.

175
00:10:48,664 --> 00:10:51,226
And then, of course, made Flash games.

176
00:10:51,226 --> 00:10:53,528
They were pretty awful.

177
00:10:55,277 --> 00:11:02,123
As a freelancer, I had to learn how to manage my own time and tasks, as well as manage client expectations.

178
00:11:02,123 --> 00:11:05,826
I was a team of one, so I had to be self-motivated and resourceful.

179
00:11:05,826 --> 00:11:10,490
There was no one to give me answers or to bail me out if something went wrong.

180
00:11:10,490 --> 00:11:13,232
I also picked up some hard skills along the way.

181
00:11:13,232 --> 00:11:18,297
I learned how to script, which eventually helped me prototype.

182
00:11:18,297 --> 00:11:22,600
I learned how to use Photoshop, which helped me create convincing mockups and fakes.

183
00:11:23,776 --> 00:11:26,599
And most importantly, I learned how to iterate.

184
00:11:26,599 --> 00:11:27,881
I didn't have a choice.

185
00:11:27,881 --> 00:11:29,443
When you're working with customers,

186
00:11:29,443 --> 00:11:32,346
they're never happy with the first version of anything.

187
00:11:32,346 --> 00:11:36,391
I had to develop thick skin and learn not to get overly

188
00:11:36,391 --> 00:11:38,153
attached to what I made.

189
00:11:38,153 --> 00:11:40,076
That is one of the most valuable skills

190
00:11:40,076 --> 00:11:41,898
I have as a designer right now.

191
00:11:44,279 --> 00:11:46,680
At that point, I'd been making games my entire life,

192
00:11:46,680 --> 00:11:49,000
but I had never even considered a job in game dev.

193
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:52,181
Everything changed when my friend Ahmed

194
00:11:52,181 --> 00:11:53,382
became a game designer.

195
00:11:53,382 --> 00:11:56,322
See, Ahmed also studied political science,

196
00:11:56,322 --> 00:11:58,043
and he was brown like me.

197
00:11:58,043 --> 00:11:59,243
And representation matters.

198
00:11:59,243 --> 00:12:02,084
Seeing him make it opened my eyes,

199
00:12:02,084 --> 00:12:04,384
and I knew I had found my colleague.

200
00:12:04,384 --> 00:12:07,345
My entire life had prepared me for this moment,

201
00:12:07,345 --> 00:12:09,586
and Ahmed thus became my first mentor.

202
00:12:10,564 --> 00:12:14,026
And over the next six months, he guided me in creating a portfolio.

203
00:12:14,026 --> 00:12:17,007
I had plenty of things already to put in a portfolio.

204
00:12:17,007 --> 00:12:19,809
I mean, I've been making things my entire life.

205
00:12:19,809 --> 00:12:24,931
So he helped me just parse the bad from the not so bad and make the good even better.

206
00:12:24,931 --> 00:12:30,494
And I must have applied to over 100 different companies at that time, all over the world.

207
00:12:30,494 --> 00:12:32,475
And I initially didn't hear back from any of them.

208
00:12:34,432 --> 00:12:38,233
I eventually got one interview, and that, luckily for me,

209
00:12:38,233 --> 00:12:39,953
translated to a game designer job.

210
00:12:39,953 --> 00:12:42,294
And I've been a game designer ever

211
00:12:42,294 --> 00:12:45,035
since, leveraging all of the aforementioned skills

212
00:12:45,035 --> 00:12:46,935
in the process.

213
00:12:46,935 --> 00:12:47,775
And that's my story.

214
00:12:47,775 --> 00:12:49,176
Thank you.

215
00:12:49,176 --> 00:12:50,136
Take it away, Marina.

216
00:12:50,136 --> 00:12:53,917
Thank you so much, Osama.

217
00:12:53,917 --> 00:12:54,997
Hello, everyone.

218
00:12:54,997 --> 00:12:57,238
I'm Marina Diaz.

219
00:12:57,238 --> 00:12:58,358
I'm 27 years old.

220
00:12:58,358 --> 00:13:01,359
I'm the CEO of my own company, Free of Caps Games.

221
00:13:01,843 --> 00:13:06,533
I'm also the lead designer of Dordogne with Angèle Secoeur Studios in France,

222
00:13:06,533 --> 00:13:11,464
and I have an undergrad in Italian and German and a master's degree in game design.

223
00:13:11,982 --> 00:13:16,025
And some of the awards that I won were Forbes 30 under 30,

224
00:13:16,025 --> 00:13:22,270
Game Dev Heroes 2020, and I'm also part of After Crew and other associations in the games industry.

225
00:13:22,270 --> 00:13:28,135
And this is what you normally see about me if you look for me on the internet.

226
00:13:28,135 --> 00:13:33,160
But now I want to tell you about what you don't see, but it's very important to know regarding

227
00:13:33,160 --> 00:13:39,705
career when you are considering starting in the games industry or even doing whatever you want to do.

228
00:13:41,235 --> 00:13:46,317
So, first of all, I wanted to become a vet. When I was a kid, I had lots and lots of dreams,

229
00:13:46,317 --> 00:13:51,998
but the biggest was to become a vet. I really loved animals, and I still love them today.

230
00:13:51,998 --> 00:13:56,879
However, my biggest dream was changing quite often. Someday I wanted to be a vet,

231
00:13:56,879 --> 00:14:01,520
any other day I wanted to be a paleontologist, any other day I wanted to be a journalist, and so on.

232
00:14:01,520 --> 00:14:06,221
But then I also discovered the big truth, that it's also one of the things that get me

233
00:14:06,221 --> 00:14:10,002
a bit far from the games industry, and it's that I'm super bad at math.

234
00:14:10,002 --> 00:14:10,262
So,

235
00:14:10,633 --> 00:14:18,700
Basically, when you're not good at math, lots of things cut from your way. But then it's when life

236
00:14:18,700 --> 00:14:25,205
started happening. And when I was five, my dad suffered a heart stroke. And then my mom needed

237
00:14:25,205 --> 00:14:30,970
